Organization.Clergy:
People of all races joined the church, and a vast majority of them were females.{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2012)/Concerning Witches}}

Due to their affinity with the [[Earth (element)|Earth]] [[domain]], [[Earth genasi]] were common amongst the clergy. They were either clerics or laypeople, and often tasked with guarding duties.

Some [[truenamer]]s joined the clergy as well, interested by the creation and cosmological structure of the Realms.{{Cite web/Class Chronicles: Truenamers}}

In the [[Uthgardt]] tribes, a clergy of female [[shaman]]s served Chauntea, which was considered the patron of women.

Organization.Titles:
; Titles {{small|(in ascending order of rank)}}
: Close One &bull; Watchful Brother / Sister of the Earth &bull; Trueseed &bull; Harvestmaster / Harvestmistress &bull; High Harvestmaster / High Harvestmistress &bull; Onum 

In addition, rural clerics referred to themselves as "Pastorals", whereas some older sects focused on the wilderness called themselves the "True Shapers".

Organization.Orders:
The clergy of Chauntea was known to have no affiliated military of knightly orders.

* The [[Sisters of the House]]: an all-female order of priestesses who tended to the [[Harvest House (Amn)|Harvest House]] in [[Amn]].

* The [[Bountiful Lady of the Vast Circle]]: a small [[druid]]ic circle active near [[Ravens Bluff]] and [[Dragon Falls (village)|Dragon Falls]].{{Cite polyhedron/119/The Druid Circle of Chauntea}}

Rituals.Holidays:
* [[Greengrass]] was a hedonistic fertility festival, during which lots of food and drinks were consumed.
* The [[High Prayers of the Harvest]] were solemn celebrations of Chauntea's bounty, held at the time a community harvested its crops. While the date wasn't strictly defined, it usually happened around [[Highharvestide]].

During or around religious holidays, priests of Chauntea would often organize agricultural fairs.{{Cite web/Candlekeep forum/Questions for Ed Greenwood (2010)/Meetings, Fairs}}

Bases.Temples:
* [[Goldenfields]], also known as the "Granary of the North", was a gigantic walled abbey hosting thousands of faithful. It was located near [[Waterdeep]].
* The [[Abbey of the Golden Sheaf]], in [[Mistledale]].
* The [[House of Bountiful Harvest]] in [[Ravens Bluff]]
* The [[Golden Bowl of the Goddess]] in [[Iriaebor]].
* Many large temples shared a similar name, the "[[Bounty of the Goddess]]". Notably, such temples could be found in [[Bounty of the Goddess (Archenbridge)|Archenbridge]] and [[Bounty of the Goddess (Voonlar)|Voonlar.]]
* Similarly many temples were called "Harvest Houses" or "Harvest Hall", such as the ones in [[Harvest House|Daggerford]], [[High Harvest Home|Elturel]], [[Harvest Hall|Wheloon]] or [[Harvest House (Amn)|Amn]].{{Cite interactive atlas|3990 Daggerford}}
* Another common name, used for small temples, was "House of Plenty". Such temples could be found in [[House of Plenty|Shadowdale]] and [[House of Plenty (Maskyr's Eye)|Maskyr's Eye]].{{Cite polyhedron/55/The Everwinking Eye: A Closer Look at Maskyr's Eye}}
* In the city of [[Hlintar]], the local temple to the Earthmother offers a "silent vault" service&mdash;a rudimentary banking system allowing customers to rent strongchests in a vault guarded against thievery by magic and monsters.{{Cite polyhedron/91/The Everwinking Eye: Treasures of the Vast, Part Three}}
* In the city of [[Emrys (town)|Emrys]], the [[Church of All Souls]] hosts several sanctuaries, including one dedicated to the Earthmother.{{Cite polyhedron/119/Elminster's Everwinking Eye: The Throat of Talduth Vale}}
* [[The Bright Sheaf]] was a walled garden temple located in the city of [[Arthyn]].{{Cite web/The Border Kingdoms/Arthyn}}
* The [[House of Sun and Earth]] was a temple dedicated to the worship of both Chauntea and [[Lathander]] in the town of [[Woody Glen]].{{Cite dungeon/67/Witches' Brew|12,15}}
* The clergy maintained a large temple in [[Easting (town)|Easting]], where the Earthmother was the primary deity.
* [[Chauntea's Cradle]] was a temple located in [[Crimmor]], the caravan capital of [[Amn]]. Its clergy maintained gardens outside the city walls, producing a variety of goods such as apples and pears.
* An unnamed temple to Chauntea, managed by druids, could be found in the [[Misty Forest]].
* The [[Rose House]] was a Chauntean chapel located in the town of [[Purskul]]. It was abandoned since its seven priests fell ill and died, ''circa'' the {{YearlinkName|1368}}.
* A temple could be found in [[Shadowdale]]. Its clergy was known to collaborate with the authorities, and helped apprehend troublemakers should guards call for help.<ref name="SotD-p3>

Equipment, Spells, & Relics.Relics:
* The [[Portal of Plenty]]: also known as "Chauntea's Blessing", this [[portal]] was built in a [[shrine]] located in [[Archendale]]. It connected to a different world where the Earthmother was also revered, and allowed the faithful of both worlds to trade agrarian goods and knowledge.{{Cite web/Perilous Gateways/Portals of the Harvest Gods:The Portal of Plenty}}
* [[The Glarathra]]: a [[holy book]] in the form of a large [[bronze]] flower, whose image adorned numerous tapestries and mosaics created by followers of the faith.
* [[Earthmother's Weapons]]: a [[holy book]] created by a druid of the [[Moonshae Isles]], and used by a [[Malarite]] druid during the mid-to-late 14{{th}} century [[DR]].{{Cite web/Earthmother's Weapons}}
* The [[Torque of the Goddess]] were silver bands worn around the neck by worshipers of the Earthmother, which granted several benefits such as a protection against [[Lycanthropy]].

document_data.History:
{{quote|Nurture, tend, and plant wherever possible...|Dogma of Chauntea}}

* The church of Chauntea was one of the main spiritual powers dominating the region of [[Athalantar]] during the 2{{nd}} to 4{{th}} Century [[DR]].

* The Chauntean faith was an important part of the religious landscape of [[Tethyr]] since its inception, but its influence decreased at the beginning of the 14{{th}} Century DR as the kingdom moved towards more mercantilism and urbanization.

* During the mid-to-late 14{{th}} Century DR, the church of Chauntea was officially declared a [[Church Royal]] of [[Cormyr]].{{Cite dungeon/198/Cormyr Royale: The Royal Court of the Forest Kingdom|49-50}} During that time period, members of the church were amongst the few petitioners asking the Crown of Cormyr to open the prison-city of [[Wheloon]] in order to allow innocents to be freed.{{Cite dungeon/198/Cormyr Royale: The Royal Court of the Forest Kingdom|56}}

* In the years immediately following the [[Second Sundering]], the timing of the seasons had shifted as [[Abeir]] separated from Toril. In response, Chauntean priests considered the possibility of changing the dates of their annual feast days.
